Cook and all,<br><br>
Cook thanks for the utility jacket.  I will do my best to wear it well.  Thanks to all for the kind words.  Ed, you're still my hero -- poet warrior.<br><br>
I explained my motivations and actions to the junior high school kids the other day with two examples of human nature.<br><br>
I first asked them when they did their weekend homework. We all know the answer was Sunday night -- that's human nature.  I said that most of us would wait until Monday morning if we could get away with it.  I said that was how I got to Vietnam.  I kept putting off &quot;the homework&quot; -- waiting for good fortune to take hold and say that it was no longer necessary or the army to say that the pins in my arm would get me discharged.  I took that attitude across the Pacific.<br><br>
I then told the kids to think about the bombing in Oklahoma City.  I said that the police could not stop looking for the bombers until they believed they were caught.  I also said that the rescuers looked through the rubble for days after most people believed all were recovered.  THAT'S HUMAN NATURE.  That's why I stayed in Vietnam.  I tried to enlist in the army in 1969 (almost two years after I got out, for that reason).  They still wouldn't take me.  I don't think I would have made it home a second time if I did.  I was still pretty frazzled.<br><br>
Ed, you once wrote that you signed on for a second tour so your little brother didn't have to go -- that's an fine example of family and how you were raised.<br><br>
Frank and I were friends before the war.  He is still married to the same woman and they raised four daughters.  BUT WE ALL DID WHAT WE DID BECAUSE OF WHO WE WERE AND HOW WE WANTED OTHERS TO THINK OF US.   To me Vietnam is a story of human nature -- without the protections of modern denail -- the raw of it and the wealth of it.<br><br>
Paul<br><br>
PS -- Think what we have done for one another on these threads.  That's impressive.  When others read our words they will have to say that these folks took some mighty hard shots and they came out of it with there sense of humor intact. <br>

